What Is KYC and Why It Matters&lt;br&gt;
KYC (Know Your Customer) is a regulatory process used by financial institutions and digital platforms to verify the identity of their users. The purpose of KYC is to:&lt;br&gt;
Prevent fraud and identity theft&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Stop money laundering and terrorist financing&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ensure regulatory compliance&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Protect customers and businesses&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Promote financial transparency&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;KYC verification typically involves:&lt;br&gt;
Government-issued ID verification&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Facial recognition or biometric validation&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Proof of address&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bank or financial documentation&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ongoing transaction monitoring&lt;/p&gt;

